# AI Workflow Architecture Rules

## Intent Recognition Pipeline
```
User Input ("/gmail compose to:foo@bar.com")
  → IntentRecognitionService.parse()
  → ParsedIntent { command, action, params, confidence }
  → CommandRouter.route(intent)
  → ConcreteCommandHandler.execute(intent, userId)
  → CommandExecutionResponse
```

## Command Handler Pattern (Strategy)
- Each slash command is a Spring `@Component` implementing `CommandHandler` interface
- CommandRouter uses a `Map<String, CommandHandler>` keyed by command name
- New commands: implement `CommandHandler`, annotate with `@Component("gmail")` → auto-registered
- Example:
```java
public interface CommandHandler {
    String getCommandName();
    CommandExecutionResponse handle(ParsedIntent intent, Long userId);
}

@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class GmailCommandHandler implements CommandHandler {
    @Override
    public String getCommandName() { return "gmail"; }
    @Override
    public CommandExecutionResponse handle(ParsedIntent intent, Long userId) { ... }
}
```

## Intent Confidence Thresholds
- confidence ≥ 0.85: execute immediately
- confidence 0.50–0.84: execute with a confirmation prompt to user
- confidence < 0.50: respond with "Did you mean...?" suggestions
- confidence = 0.0 (unknown command): return available commands list

## AI Upgrade Path (v1 → v2)
- v1 (current): Rule-based regex parser in `IntentRecognitionService`
- v2 (planned): Replace with OpenAI function calling or local Ollama model
- v3 (future): Fine-tuned model on user command history
- Keep the `IntentRecognitionService` interface stable — implementation is swappable

## Command Execution Logging
- Every command execution is logged to `command_executions` table (Flyway V2)
- Log: userId, rawInput, parsedIntent (JSONB), status, executionMs, result
- This data is the foundation for AI personalization in v2

## Integration Handler Rules
- Gmail/GitHub integrations store OAuth tokens in `integration_tokens` table
- Token refresh is handled transparently in the integration service layer
- Never call external APIs synchronously from the command execution path — use async where possible
- Rate limit integration calls per user (prevent abuse of OAuth tokens)

## Frontend Command Bar Rules
- Debounce autocomplete suggestions: 300ms after last keystroke
- Show command suggestions when input starts with '/'
- Keyboard shortcuts: `Cmd/Ctrl+K` to open, `Escape` to close, `Tab` to autocomplete
- Loading state must be shown for commands taking >200ms
- Error messages from backend must be displayed inline — never silently fail
